''''' Volcanoes: Life on the Edge''''' is a 1996 interactive CD-ROM published by Corbis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-03-31/business/9603310356_1_volcanoes-krakatau-eruption|title=Volcanoes: Life on the Edge Produced by Corbis Corp...|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=31 March 1996|author=Robert Enstad}}</ref> It recounts the adventure of photojournalist Roger Russmeyer, who spent a series of months chasing volcanoes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=K8IS2A_xDLUC&pg=PA381&lpg=PA381&dq=corbis+%22Volcanoes:+Life+on+the+Edge%22&source=bl&ots=Pfl4mTOQG5&sig=ap7RpX2ZgKewWXNx_Kic-BI_ju4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIjYS718raAhUMXrwKHRyyBTM4ChDoAQg_MAg#v=onepage&q=corbis+%22Volcanoes:+Life+on+the+Edge%22&f=false|title=PC Mag|first=Ziff Davis|last=Inc|date=9 April 1996|publisher=Ziff Davis, Inc.|via=Google Books}}</ref> Discover Magazine deemed it a satisfying title about Earth science.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://discovermagazine.com/1997/dec/tokensofsciencec1289|title=Tokens of Science: CD-ROMs - DiscoverMagazine.com|publisher=}}</ref> Technology Review deemed the title both the most conventional and arresting of Corbis' output.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/400162/setting-a-standard-in-multimedia-software/|title=Setting A Standard In Multimedia Software|first=Wade|last=Roush|publisher=}}</ref> Newsweek described the project as "well-wrought".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/thar-she-blows-179828|title=Thar She Blows|date=4 February 1996|publisher=}}</ref> The Washington Post deemed it a first-rate CD-ROM documentary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/business/technology/1996/11/28/nerdy-but-nice/74f96495-f839-4683-b2f9-51f7155cb424/|title=NERDY BUT NICE|date=28 November 1996|publisher=|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref> The Sydney Morning Herald disliked the " humdrum photo-essays about low-key eruptions".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/120110873/|title=The Sydney Morning Herald from Sydney, New South Wales|date=26 July 1997|page=182|publisher=}}</ref> After releasing ''[[A Passion for Art: Renoir, Cezanne, Matisse, and Dr. Barnes]]''; ''[[Critical Mass: America's Race to Build the Atomic Bomb]]''; and ''Volcanoes: Life on the Edge'', Corbis gained a reputation for high quality work.<ref>http://digitalcommons.lmu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2022&context=llr</ref> MacUser praised the well-organised interface<ref>http://vintageapple.org/macuser/pdf/MacUser_9612_December_1996.pdf</ref> while Popular Science enjoyed the "stunning" photographs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WpVTOroeFJIC&pg=PA17&dq=corbis+%22Volcanoes:+Life+on+the+Edge%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSkNbf18raAhUJjLwKHdwtB8AQ6AEIPDAE#v=onepage&q=corbis+%22Volcanoes:+Life+on+the+Edge%22&f=false|title=Popular Science|first=Bonnier|last=Corporation|date=1 April 1996|publisher=Bonnier Corporation|via=Google Books}}</ref> MacWorld gave the game 7.2/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=YaxVAAAAMAAJ&q=corbis+%22Volcanoes:+Life+on+the+Edge%22&dq=corbis+%22Volcanoes:+Life+on+the+Edge%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSkNbf18raAhUJjLwKHdwtB8AQ6AEIRjAG|title=Macworld: The Macintosh Magazine|date=1 July 1996|publisher=PC World Communications|via=Google Books}}</ref>
